post_text:
Good Day,

The Administration has made a decision to move the July 25th Graduation program outdoors as well as moving the start time of the event to 10:00 AM. The opinion of the Administration is that the outdoor venue provides better social distancing options and thus a safer environment for all choosing to attend. Limits to attendees for all families with a graduate are still in place. The time change is intended to provide a more pleasant temperature for the event.

post_text:
"After consultation with our Health Department and other State and Local officials, it has been determined that all schools in the ESU 5 Region will be closed through Friday, May 1st, with the possibility of schools being closed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. This decision will be re-evaluated as circumstances change, and another announcement will be made on April 22nd concerning the rest of the 2019-2020 school year. This is a precautionary public health measure; local health and school officials are monitoring the COVID-19 situation in Southeast Nebraska closely. School Superintendents met with Public Health Solutions and determined that this action would help prevent exposure to our area to flatten the curve and decrease the spread of disease. "

Randy M. Page

From Thayer Central Community Schools:

The Strategic Planning meetings for the scheduled for 5:30 PM and 7:00PM tonight, March 16th have been postponed indefinitely. Due to concerns with COVID19 spread and CDC guidelines concerning the appropriate size of gatherings Thayer Central has postponed tonight's meetings. At an appropriate time the school district will contact the public with the rescheduled dates and times of these meetings.

Thank you for understanding the schools need to manage this and for working with your school district on this matter.

Randy Page, Thayer Central Superintendent

post_text:
Following is a video made because your Superintendent lost a bet with seven 5th Grade girls over the Super Bowl! All in good fun, the stakes consisted of wearing a, “Chiefs Win!!” sign and making a video. Had I won the girls were to read two chapter books in 8 days and wear a Chicago Bears jersey for half a school day, per each student!

Life can be like a high stakes sporting event in many ways; Hard Work, Commitment, Skill Development, Teamwork, and a Positive Attitude all make a difference. We learn to win like a Champion, we learn to lose with dignity, this is the Titan Way!

What a great way to connect with kids and promote positive life-skills!!! Here is our video…

All in good fun, the stakes consisted of wearing a, “Chiefs Win!!” sign and making a video. Had I won the girls were to read two chapter books in 8 days and wear a Chicago Bears jersey for half a school day, per each student!

Life can be like a high stakes sporting event in many ways; Hard Work, Commitment, Skill Development, Teamwork, and a Positive Attitude all make a difference. We learn to win like a Champion, we learn to lose with dignity, this is the Titan Way!

What a great way to connect with kids and promote positive life-skills!!! Here is our video…

post_text: The freshmen class of 2023 will be selling Christmas wreaths as a fundraising activity. Sales start on Wednesday, October 9, and end on Wednesday, November 6. The wreaths need to be paid for at the time of ordering. Customers may pay in cash or check made out to Thayer Central Schools. All of the Christmas wreaths will be made in Belleville, Kansas, at the Kasl Tree Farm. Each 12” wreath will come decorated with red ribbon bows, pinecones and holly berries. Each wreath is dipped in a preservative to help aid in moisture and needle retention. Wreaths will be delivered to you during the first week of December or just before. If you have any questions feel free to contact freshmen class sponsor Josh Lanik at school, (402) 768-6117 or by email: josh.lanik@thayercentral.net.
